[normal]How StreetGames increase[bold]s[bold] female sports participation by providing activities that are delivered in an appropriate and effective way[bold]1.35
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Our successful track record helped StreetGames to secure a £3.38 million National Lottery
[normal] award from Sport England in 2013 to set up over 300 Doorst
[normal]ep Sport Clubs (DSCs) in disadvantaged communities by March 2014.  
[normal]1.36
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The initiative, which forms part of a wider DCMS/Sport England youth sport strategy aims to reduce the drop out in sport and help disadvantaged young people to develop a sporting habit for
[normal] life. Our 
[normal]target
[normal] is for 30% of the young people participating in the DSC programme to be female. We will use the Us Girls branding, the insight gained and the lessons learned from the Us Girls 
[normal]programme 
[normal]to help us achieve this target.
[normal]1.37
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We will do this by p
[normal]roviding a fun, exciting and vibrant place where teenage girls and young women play sports, at a low cost, right on their doorstep in a style that is attractive to them. Young women will be able to take part in a range of sports, which will include dance a
[normal]nd fitness, non-traditional sports and adapted versions of games as well as more traditional sports. They will also be given the opportunity to take part in local sports festivals, get involved in volunteering, leadership or training should they wish to do
[normal] so.  
[normal]1.38
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]StreetGames will also support DSCs to create a vibrant and varied sporting offer all year round to encourage attendance and retention, e.g. via incentives, competitions, group trips, events and links to health and wellbeing activities.  
[normal]1.39
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We are conf
[normal]ident that DSCs will attract thousands of young women to participate in sport – but are realistic: alone, this initiative cannot re-dress the current gender disparities that exist.  We
[normal] are therefore, working with other partners in the women’s sport network
[normal] to do this. This includes Women’s Sport Trust, Women’s Sport Net, WSFF, Sportsister and other influential females that champion women’s sport including journalists, presenters, business women and athletes.
[normal]1.40
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Many NGB programmes are not particularly geared t
[normal]owards the 
[normal]female
[normal] market. We are working with NGBs to share the learning from the Us Girls programme
[normal] 
[normal]but much more needs to be done. England Netball is a fantastic example of an NGB that has used research and insight to develop a 
[normal]participant
[normal] 
[normal]centred
[normal] approa
[normal]ch to provide products and programmes that women want.
[normal] 
[normal]There is a lot to be learnt from the success of netball in engaging a large number of females in sport.
[normal]1.41
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]M
[normal]uch more needs to be done and would welcome lobbying and support to drive this further.  We 
[normal]believe, that the industry has the ‘know how’ – it just needs resources to ‘turbo charge’ action.
[normal]Us Girls Initiatives &amp; Programmes[bold]1.42
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Us Girls has developed a number of initiatives and progr
[normal]ammes to help 
[normal]achieve its aims and
[normal] objectives:
[normal]Our female only fe
[normal]stival programme.
[normal] 
[normal]Us
[normal] Girls Rocks festivals give girls aged 14+ 
[normal]the 
[normal]opportunity to try traditional and non-traditional sports, along with a combination of other activities such as health and wellbeing information and beauty treatments. The festivals are fun
[normal], non-threatening and are held at a local 
[normal]and regional level. 
[normal]Gear4Girls is a new initiative which aims to raise money to supply sports 
[normal]equipment and 
[normal]clothing to young women and girls from disadvantage communities, people who want to get active but don’t
[normal] have any gear!  As well as raising funds, a host of NGBs are donating equipment to the initiative which can then be distributed to where it’s needed.
[normal] 
[normal]Us
[normal] Girls launched its Gear4Girls Campaign on International Women’s Day, headed up by our president Nicola
[normal] 
[normal]Adams.
[normal]#GirlsTimeToMakeItHappen is a campaign to develop more opportunities for 
[normal]young 
[normal]women to take part in sport. We are keen to develop and grow the number of organisations delivering good sport for young women. We have also signed up Us Girls Champion
[normal]s from Team GB to support this effort. Nicola Adams has been signed up as Us Girls President. Other Us Girls Champions include Sophie Cox (GB Judo), Sarah Stevenson (GB Taekwondo) &amp; Kate Grey (Paralympic swimmer &amp; commentator), plus several others (see web
[normal]site for more 
[normal]details). 
[normal]Us Girls Alive, is a new strand of the existing Us Girls programme and support
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]young female volunteers to assist in the development of Us Girls Alive clubs 
[normal](like an interactive magazine) 
[normal]and the signposting to local physical 
[normal]activity programmes across the country until September 2015. With £395,839 in funding from the Health and Social Care Volunteering Fund from the Department of Health, Us Girls Alive promote
[normal]s
[normal] volunteering as the key to health improvements for young women li
[normal]ving in
[normal] disadvantaged communities in 19
[normal] 
[normal]areas in England
[normal].
